         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">3/3/80. ¶  ¶ Herewith, dear Sir Joseph, I beg to send you some pinnae of a Polypodium (or perhaps Aspidium) from extra-tropical East-Australia, concerning which some misapprehension has prevailed sinc...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">80.03.03</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">To Joseph Hooker</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">RBG Kew. Kew Correspondence, Australia, Mueller. 1871-81. ff. 258-259.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">3/3/80.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Herewith, dear Sir Joseph, I beg to send you some pinnae of a Polypodium (or perhaps Aspidium) from extra-tropical East-Australia, concerning which some misapprehension has prevailed since many years. Your great parent noted it in his own handwriting in my collection as a variety of Aspidium decompositum,<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn0" n="1">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3347in; text-indent: -0.3347in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>A search at MEL has failed to find a specimen with such a note by William Hooker.</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>possibly mislead by my own sorting of the specimens. In this view I followed Sir Will. Hooker (fragm. V, 137),<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn1" n="2">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3347in; text-indent: -0.3347in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>B66.02.01,<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>pp. 136-7.</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>stating however that the rhizomes needed comparison &amp; keeping this Polypodium at least as a<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
               <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">var.</hi>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>apart. Since, the Rev. Dr Wools and Mr Bailey, who lived among these ferns, have assured me, that the Polypodium - now forwarded - has<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
               <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">never</hi>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>any indusium; it differs also in the narrower more sharply teethed lobes &amp; in the rhizomes.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I am not sure, whether it is identical with Lastraea davalloides<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn2" n="3">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3347in; text-indent: -0.3347in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Lastrea davallioides?</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>of Brakenridge,<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn3" n="4">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3347in; text-indent: -0.3347in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Brackenridge? Brackenridge (1854-5).</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>as I have no authentic specimen to compare, but Aspidium or Polypodium effusum, of which Grisebach distinctly says, that its indusium is often suppressed, comes evidently near to it, from what I see of South American specimens.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>As this fern is sure to come under cultivation, if indeed it is not already so in your conservatories, you will be interested in it, and so you or Dr Baker may think it worthwhile to see what it really is. If new, I like to see it named in honor of Mr Bailey, as he and the Rev. Dr Woolls have the credit, to have independently shown its perfect specific distinction from A. decompositum.<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn4" n="5">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3347in; text-indent: -0.3347in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                           <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        </seg>
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>The only fern named by Baker with a specific epithet honouring Bailey that is listed in IPNI is<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-style: italic; ">Gymnogramma baileyi<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        </seg>in<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-style: italic; ">Kew Bulletin<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        </seg>(1892). See annotation transcribed in n.<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>11<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>below.</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>I have it from the following localities: Genoa, F.v.M., Mt Dromedary, Reader; Illawarra, Moore; Nepean, Woolls; Blue Mountains, Mrs Calvert; New England, C. Stuart; Cloud's Creek, Dr Beckler; New England, C. Stuart;<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn5" n="6">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3347in; text-indent: -0.3347in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>It is not clear whether M had two separate collections by Stuart from New England, or whether the repetition is an error.</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>Clarence River, M Gillivray;<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn6" n="7">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3347in; text-indent: -0.3347in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                           <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        </seg>
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>M'Gillivray?</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>Richmond River, Fawcett;<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn7" n="8">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3347in; text-indent: -0.3347in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                           <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>C. H. Fawcett.</seg>
                     </p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>Brisbane-River, Bailey; Condamine-River, Hartmann.<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn8" n="9">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3347in; text-indent: -0.3347in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                           <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Carl Hartmann.</seg>
                     </p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>From an original specimen, obtained from Vienne, I find that Nephrodium colanthum<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn9" n="10">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3347in; text-indent: -0.3347in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Nephrodium calanthum?</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>of Norfolk Island is the real N. decompositum.</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">Regardfully your</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Ferd. von Mueller.<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn10" n="11">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3347in; text-indent: -0.3347in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-style: italic; ">Annotation below signature:</seg>
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>This looks to me, spite of its want of involucre, a mere variety of<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                           <hi rend="underline">Nephrodium decompositum</hi>
                        </seg>. Polypodium Rufescens, Blume, is, I think, an Anal[a]gous form of the less-divided variety of the same species. | J G B. [John Gilbert Baker].</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; margin-right: -0.2388in; "
               xml:lang="en">Allow me to ask you, dear Sir Joseph, whether you met among Cruciferae any species, in which the color of the petals varies yellow and white? You must have seen an enormous lot of these plants, when working for the “genera”<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn11" n="12">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3347in; text-indent: -0.3347in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Bentham<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>&amp;<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>Hooker (1862–83).</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>on this order. I believe, that I have two species, one a Capsella, the other an Erysimum, which have the petals yellow &amp; white (or pink) also, but not on the same spot of growth. Thus I was unable to affirm, whether they are mere varieties. As a rule, the color in this respect is very constant, altho'<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>all colors vary white exceptionally, but here the white of the two is prevalent.<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn12" n="13">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3347in; text-indent: -0.3347in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>See J. Hooker to M, 28 April 1880.</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
            </p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">Regardfully your</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Ferd. von Mueller.<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn13" n="14">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3347in; text-indent: -0.3347in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; margin-right: -0.2388in; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>The first postscript paragraph is on a separate sheet of paper, f. 262 in the guard book, and has an annotation<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>'16/4/80'<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>written in red ink diagonally across the text in an unknown hand. The date is presumably when the item was received at Kew. It has been associated with this letter on the basis of the annotation and because topics in this postscript and in the body of the letter are discussed in J. Hooker to M, 28 April 1880. The sheet is signed, but there are other cases of M signing undoubted postscripts.</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">Could not<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>Celmisia<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>longifolia<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>be naturalized in England? with<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>Gentiana<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>saxosa?<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn14" n="15">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3347in; text-indent: -0.3347in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>The second postscript paragraph is on a separate sheet of paper, f. 263 in the guard book, and is placed here because the annotation<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>'cf Raphanus'<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>in red ink relates to J. Hooker to M, 28 April 1880.</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
            </p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
